{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504002"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:08:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:08:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2093"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2093"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.63,0.07,0.06,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114347"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2093"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96347"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1816"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27268"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34721"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34887"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42459"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47453"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114347"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic to discuss pregnancy planning. She has a five-year history of essential hypertension well controlled on ramipril. She has no other medical conditions and takes no other regular medications. She and her partner have been trying to conceive for the past month.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. BMI is 35 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management of her antihypertensive medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue ramipril as it is well controlled","Change to methyldopa","Change to amlodipine","Change to atenolol","Change to nifedipine immediate release"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient requires immediate modification of her antihypertensive medication as she is actively trying to conceive while taking an ACE inhibitor. ACE inhibitors and angiotensin receptor blockers are absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy due to their association with major congenital abnormalities, including fetal renal dysfunction, oligohydramnios, growth restriction, and skull defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethyldopa\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as it has the longest track record of safety in pregnancy and is considered a first-line agent. It has been extensively studied with no evidence of teratogenicity or adverse fetal effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue ramipril\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as ACE inhibitors can cause fetal harm even in early pregnancy. The risk of exposure during organogenesis makes it essential to change medications before conception rather than waiting for a confirmed pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Enifedipine\u003C/strong\u003E, while sometimes used in pregnancy, are generally considered second-line agents. If nifedipine is to be used for long term management then sustained release preparation should be used. Immediate release nifedipine is generally used for emergency management of hypertension in pregnancy. Furthermore, nifedipine is not typically used in first trimester; instead, methyldopa is preferred in view of extensive safety data.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtenolol\u003C/strong\u003E should be avoided in pregnancy as it has been associated with fetal growth restriction. If a beta-blocker is needed, labetalol is preferred due to its better safety profile.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in managing hypertension in women planning pregnancy is to transition to medications with established safety profiles before conception occurs. This allows for dose adjustment and ensures stable blood pressure control with appropriate medications before pregnancy begins.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ACE inhibitors and angiotensin receptor blockers must be ceased before conception due to risk of fetal abnormalities.","Methyldopa is a safe first-line antihypertensive medication for use during pregnancy.","Women with chronic hypertension should transition to pregnancy-safe medications before attempting conception."],"references":["Braunthal S, Brateanu A. Hypertension in pregnancy: Pathophysiology and treatment. SAGE Open Med. 2019;7:2050312119843700-. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31007914/","Society of Obstetric Medicine of Australia and New Zealand (SOMANZ). Hypertension in pregnancy: guideline 2023. Updated 30 June 2023. Sydney: SOMANZ; 2023. Available from: https://www.somanz.org/content/uploads/2023/06/SOMANZ_Hypertension_in_Pregnancy_Guideline_2023_Updated_30.6.23.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96347"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2093"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96347"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T18:49:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T18:49:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2093"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114347"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.